resource.comment:
(Interpretation) Immunity indicates detectable levels of
antibody or prior exposure to the virus but does not exclude
the possibility of an ongoing infection.  Testing on acute
and convalescent phase sera or an assay for the presence of
IgM Varicella antibody should be used to diagnose recent
infection.
Limitation; There is an increased incidence of false
positive results from immunocompromised patients. It is
recommended that immunocompromised patients be tested by
another method to confirm a positive result.

resource.comment:
INTERPRETIVE INFORMATION: Mumps Ab, IgG by CIA

  8.9 AU/mL or less .... Negative - No significant level of
                         detectable IgG mumps virus antibody

  9.0-10.9 AU/mL ....... Equivocal - Repeat testing in 10-14
                         days may be helpful

  11.0 AU/mL or greater: Positive - IgG antibody to mumps
                         virus detected, which may indicate
                         a current or past exposure/
                         immunization to mumps virus. 

The best evidence for current infection is a significant change on 
two appropriately timed specimens, where both tests are done in 
the same laboratory at the same time.
